ar wind blowing a bubble in the\npreceding slow wind at a radial distance of order 10 pc. (3) More distant\nclouds within the host galaxy lie between 30-2500 pc, where they have been\nionized by the burst. (4-6) The massive star wind has clumps with radii and\nover-densities of 0.022, 0.063, and 0.12 parsecs and 50%, 10%, and 10%\nrespectively. The immediate progenitor of the burster could either be a WC-type\nWolf-Rayet star or a highly evolved star whose original mass was just too small\nfor it to become a WN-type Wolf-Rayet star.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 9 Nov 2002 20:40:35 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 18 Feb 2003 23:44:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-11-07"}
